	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Major challenges facing Fiji sugar sector</h1>

			
			<h4>
												02 May 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Lack of capital to renew key equipment has led the Fiji Sugar Corporation (FSC) to launch a comprehensive mill maintenance programme which may delay the start of the cane crushing season. This is seen as necessary to cut the number of crushing days lost due to breakdowns.</p><p>A World Bank regional economic update suggests that the causes of decline of Fiji’s sugar sector are deep-rooted and complex, and that reversing the current trends represents ‘a formidable challenge’. The Fijian government is currently reviewing IMF recommendations on the future of the sugar sector which argue for divestment of government control within 3 years. This needs to be seen against the background of net losses in the year to 31 May 2010 of 175 million Fiji dollars (€67m) and total losses between 2004 and 2007 of F$315.3m (€120.8m) on a turnover of F$2.4 bn (€919.68m).</p><p>The current debates need to be seen in the context of the relative dimension of non-sugar agricultural sectors in Fiji, where efforts to boost production of a range of crops for local markets (including the local tourism market) and efforts to improve value chains appear to be yielding results. This however needs to be seen against the background in some product areas of tariffs and other border measures which can provide protection equivalent to a 42% tariff.</p><p>The Fijian government, however, continues to assert the centrality of the sugar sector to the future of agriculture in Fiji, devoting F$123m (€47.134m) of government budget resources to reviving the sugar sector in 2011.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
