<a href="http://www.pina.com.fj/index.php?p=pacnews&amp;m=read&amp;o=16143909474d7feeee11d670ade16f" target="_self">http://www.pina.com.fj/index.php?p=pacnews&amp;m=read&amp;o=16143909474d...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The future of the Fijian sugar industry appears surrounded by contradictions, with contrasting viewpoints when on the outside looking in, and on the inside looking out. Thus, while the IMF argues for divestment, the Fijian government aims for greater nationalisation of the industry. The IMF perspective is based on the historical decline of the industry, underlined by accumulating financial losses in recent years, and the unfavourable results of industry reforms. It pins its hope on a positive response to a divestment initiative by the private sector, in a context where the private sector had already demonstrated its lack of confidence in the industry by its low response to an earlier loan proposal backed by government guarantee. This reflects considerable reservations on the part of the private sector as to the future of the industry.</p><p>The government’s nationalising view is based on the belief that there is no other industry in the country that can replace the sugar industry in the near future. The sugar industry is a major contributor to Fiji’s GDP, and its collapse is seen as being beyond contemplation. The government is therefore committed to sustaining the sugar sector, as a bridge to possible future privatisation in the longer term. However, serious capacity constraints are faced by the government in building this bridge to the future.</p><p>It is clear that the government needs to channel more resources into the sector than is provided for in the 2011 budget. It is against this background that possible future ‘aid for trade’ priorities need to be seen. The current suspension of EU aid programmes, including funding under the sugar protocol accompanying measures, holds back development of a more viable basis for the future privatisation of the sugar sector. At present, only regionally sourced funding is available and these resources are relatively limited, given the level of support needed.</p><p>Nevertheless, these regional resources could play a role in promoting and sustaining the growth which is already evident in non-sugar sectors. This could then serve to take up some of the slack arising from the establishment of a leaner and meaner sugar industry, ready for privatisation.</p>
		</div>
		
